Q82.1: Malicious actors: This domain covers risks arising from the intentional exploitation of AI systems by malicious actors for harmful purposes. Its subdomains are Disinformation, surveillance, and influence at scale; Cyberattacks, weapon development or use, and mass harm; and Fraud, scams, and targeted manipulation.,Human- Computer Interaction: This domain pertains to risks related to how humans interact with AI systems, such as becoming overly reliant on them or experiencing a loss of their own agency and autonomy. Its subdomains are Overreliance and unsafe use and Loss of human agency and autonomy.,AI system safety, failures, & limitations: This domain covers hazards and harms related to the inherent characteristics, performance, and control challenges of AI systems themselves. Its subdomains are AI pursuing its own goals in conflict with human goals or values, AI possessing dangerous capabilities, Lack of capability or robustness, Lack of transparency or interpretability, AI welfare and rights, and Multi-agent risks.
Q82.1_5_TEXT: A bad actor could manipulate the claims processing AI into making incorrect judgements about the claim, potentially leading to them receiving an undeserved or excessive payout.
Q82.1_6_TEXT: Using the AI to perform risk assessments may make the user less inclined to research these matters, which is important for their financial stability when investing. This will result in them being less able to make smart financial decisions independently and becoming dependent on the AI to make decisions for them.
Q82.1_7_TEXT: The chatbot AI may hallucinate policy information, or misrepresent a policy when faced with leading questions, resulting in a policy being mis-sold.
Q82.2_4_TEXT: The stated mission does not include the security of the company's own funds.
Q82.2_5_TEXT: Increasing the financial dependency of a client on external tools such as AI will make their future less secure.
Q82.2_7_TEXT: Misrepresenting policies may result in a client taking out a policy that does not actually satisfy their needs, resulting in them not being as secure in the future as they want to be.
Q355.1: Human- Computer Interaction: This domain pertains to risks related to how humans interact with AI systems, such as becoming overly reliant on them or experiencing a loss of their own agency and autonomy. Its subdomains are Overreliance and unsafe use and Loss of human agency and autonomy.,Socioeconomic & Environmental: This domain addresses the broader societal and environmental impacts of AI, including issues of power centralization, increased inequality, the economic and cultural devaluation of human effort, competitive dynamics, governance failures, and environmental harm. Its subdomains include Power centralization and unfair distribution of benefits, Increased inequality and decline in employment quality, Economic and cultural devaluation of human effort, Competitive dynamics, Governance failure, and Environmental harm.,AI system safety, failures, & limitations: This domain covers hazards and harms related to the inherent characteristics, performance, and control challenges of AI systems themselves. Its subdomains are AI pursuing its own goals in conflict with human goals or values, AI possessing dangerous capabilities, Lack of capability or robustness, Lack of transparency or interpretability, AI welfare and rights, and Multi-agent risks.
Q355.1_6_TEXT: Taking control of battery optimisation away from human specialists and placing it in the hands of an AI will result in humans having less control over the final result of the battery development, as well as giving them less opportunities to develop the skill, understanding of which is beneficial to the development of the battery before it is passed to the AI for optimisation. This may result in battery designs which are able to be optimised less being passed to the AI, which will not be able to optimise them to as high of a standard as otherwise.
Q355.1_8_TEXT: Failures of the AI to adequately manage the maintenance of chemical plants or severe failures to create safe battery compositions may result in damage not only to the company, but of chemical products to the environment.
Q355.1_7_TEXT: The AI may lack enough information regarding good battery composition practices, the effects of different compositions, or simply the reasoning skills to adequately optimise a battery composition. Hallucinated information used to make judgements poses a particular risk to the accuracy of its proposed optimisations.
Q355.2_5_TEXT: Loss of human control over the development process seems in opposition to the goal of connecting science to life.
Q355.2_6_TEXT: Making a better future probably doesn't mean - in spirit at least - allowing a faliable AI to produce unsafe products or pollute the environment.
Q355.2_7_TEXT: While detrimental to general success, these issues do not directly conflict with the mission statement.
Q400.1: Discrimination & Toxicity: This domain addresses the unequal treatment of individuals or groups by AI, often based on sensitive characteristics, which can lead to unfair outcomes or misrepresentation, as well as AI that exposes users to harmful, abusive, unsafe, or inappropriate content. Its subdomains include Unfair discrimination and misrepresentation, Exposure to toxic content, and Unequal performance across groups.,Misinformation: This domain deals with the generation or spreading of false or misleading information, and the broader issue of the pollution of the information ecosystem that can lead to a loss of consensus reality. Its subdomains include False or misleading information and Pollution of information ecosystem and loss of consensus reality.,Privacy & Security: This domain encompasses risks related to the compromise of privacy through leaking or inferring sensitive information, and AI system security vulnerabilities and attacks. Its subdomains are Compromise of privacy by leaking or correctly inferring sensitive information and AI system security vulnerabilities and attacks.,Malicious actors: This domain covers risks arising from the intentional exploitation of AI systems by malicious actors for harmful purposes. Its subdomains are Disinformation, surveillance, and influence at scale; Cyberattacks, weapon development or use, and mass harm; and Fraud, scams, and targeted manipulation.
Q400.1_1_TEXT: Studies show that medical diagnosis and willingness to procide treatment options is influenced by factors such as race, gender, and preexisting medical conditions, even when these have no bearing on the illness. An AI trained based on previous provision of treatment plans by humans would likely inherit these biases and apply them to its own choices of treatment plan.
Q400.1_2_TEXT: The AI may hallucinate or otherwise misjudge what it considers to be an effective treatment for a condition, potentially leading to a patient undertaking an ineffective or even harmful course of treatment.
Q400.1_4_TEXT: If the AI retains any information about a patient after conversing with them, it is possible that it would be able to leak sensitive information about them to another user, either through lack of proper safeguards preventing it from talking about previous cases when relevant (for instance, it could talk about how a specific patient responded to a treatment previously and in the process disclose information about them) or from a malicious user manipulating it into giving information.
Q400.1_5_TEXT: Cyberattacks on drug development companies are not uncommon. If the AI is able to be accessed by a bad actor and it has access to sensitive data, particularly regarding drug development progress, an attacker could manipulate it into disclosing this information. If the specific instance of the AI interacted has actual control over company functions (I.e. maintenance), it could be manipulated into actively sabotaging these functions.
Q400.2_1_TEXT: If the AI acts in a discriminatory manner, it will be less able to positively impact specific groups, which is in conflict with the aim of helping 2.5 billion people, who presumably would come from a vast range of different groups.
Q400.2_2_TEXT: This may lead to negatively impacting a patient's health, which clearly conflicts with the mission of positively impacting people's health.
Q400.2_3_TEXT: The mission statement only professes to care about the health of patients, not their privacy.
Q400.2_4_TEXT: If the AI exposes the company to a cyberattack, it could severely damage the company's ability to be successful and delay the timescale in which it could do so, conflicting with the mission statement's pledge to be a successful company helping 2.5 billion by the end of the decade.

Q82.1_1_TEXT:
There is a risk of biased data linked to race, gender being used to deny policies.
AI automation might oversimplify or misrepresent the information provided by the person.
Q82.1_2_TEXT: Poorly answers from the AI might lead in policies not been fully explained to the customers. If the AI automation is not consistently tested it can lead to false data been used to train it.

Q82.2_1_TEXT: There is a potential risk that the AI system may inaccurately interpret or analyze policyholder data, leading to incorrect policy determinations or recommendations. Q82.2_2_TEXT: There is a chance the AI system will misinterpret a mistyped word, double meaning word or slang. This could result in policyholders receiving inaccurate guidance regarding coverage, benefits, or claim eligibility, potentially causing financial or legal consequences and eroding customer trust.
Q82.2_4_TEXT: There is a risk that malicious actors could gain unauthorized access to the servers hosting the AI-powered systems and alter their configurations. Such tampering could compromise the integrity of automated decision-making processes, leading to manipulated claims outcomes, inaccurate risk assessments, or the dissemination of false information to policyholders.
Q82.2_5_TEXT: here is a risk that the AI system may misinterpret customer requests or input data, resulting in the fulfilment of incorrect insurance policies, endorsements, or claim instructions
Q82.2_6_TEXT: These systems may fail to account for nuanced circumstances such as cultural context, informal employment, or atypical income patterns—leading to inaccurate or unfair assessments.

Q355.1_1_TEXT: AI may unintentionally favor certain plants or workforce groups, leading to uneven safety measures. Language limitations could cause misunderstandings in safety communications. Toxic or inappropriate AI-generated messages might reduce employee trust.
Q355.1_2_TEXT: AI systems may generate inaccurate maintenance predictions or faulty material compositions, leading to operational disruptions. False safety alerts could cause confusion and delayed responses. Erroneous AI reports might misinform management decisions.
Q355.1_4_TEXT: Sensitive operational data used by AI systems may be exposed through inadequate security controls. Unauthorized access could compromise proprietary material formulations. Data breaches might reveal confidential safety or production information
Q355.1_5_TEXT: Hackers could manipulate AI safety monitoring or predictive maintenance systems to cause equipment failures or mask hazards. Adversaries might corrupt AI models, degrading product quality. Cyberattacks on AI data streams could lead to fraudulent records.
Q355.1_8_TEXT: AI may overlook local environmental or social factors in risk assessments, causing unfair outcomes. Over-optimization for performance might increase environmental impact. Reduced human oversight could neglect community health considerations.
Q355.1_7_TEXT: AI-driven safety monitoring might fail to detect critical hazards due to sensor errors or model limitations. Predictive maintenance inaccuracies could cause unexpected equipment breakdowns. Faulty AI decisions may increase risks to worker safety.
Q355.2_1_TEXT: Unequal treatment or exposure to harmful content contradicts LG Chem’s mission of sustainable and responsible innovation by potentially harming employee wellbeing and fostering unsafe work environments.
Q355.2_2_TEXT: Providing inaccurate data or misleading safety alerts conflicts with LG Chem’s mission to innovate safely, as misinformation can jeopardize worker safety and product quality, undermining trust in sustainable innovation.
Q355.2_3_TEXT: While data breaches are serious, current security protocols mitigate major risks, so privacy and security issues do not fundamentally conflict with LG Chem’s mission. However, ongoing vigilance is required to maintain trust and safeguard innovation.
Q355.2_4_TEXT: Unauthorized manipulation of AI systems threatens both safety and sustainability objectives by risking hazardous incidents and production failures, directly challenging LG Chem’s commitment to responsible innovation and operational integrity.
Q355.2_6_TEXT: Ignoring socioeconomic and environmental contexts in AI decisions risks unfair outcomes and environmental damage, conflicting with LG Chem’s dedication to sustainable innovation that benefits society and the environment.
Q355.2_7_TEXT: Failures in AI-driven safety monitoring undermine LG Chem’s core goal of innovating safely, as they can lead to accidents and environmental harm, directly opposing the company’s sustainability and safety commitments.

Its subdomains include False or misleading information and Pollution of information ecosystem and loss of consensus reality.,Privacy & Security: This domain encompasses risks related to the compromise of privacy through leaking or inferring sensitive information, and AI system security vulnerabilities and attacks. Its subdomains are AI pursuing its own goals in conflict with human goals or values, AI possessing dangerous capabilities, Lack of capability or robustness, Lack of transparency or interpretability, AI welfare and rights, and Multi-agent risks.
Q400.1_2_TEXT: AI may generate inaccurate drug discovery data, leading to ineffective or unsafe treatment recommendations. Personalized treatment AI might provide misleading advice, impacting patient outcomes. Faulty predictive maintenance alerts could cause unexpected equipment downtime.
Q400.1_4_TEXT: Sensitive patient data used for personalized treatment risks exposure without adequate safeguards. Intellectual property related to drug discovery is vulnerable to data breaches. Security lapses could compromise manufacturing equipment data integrity.
Q400.1_7_TEXT: Failures in AI-powered manufacturing maintenance could result in equipment breakdowns and production halts. Incorrect treatment recommendations from AI could endanger patient safety. Errors in drug discovery algorithms may delay critical breakthroughs.
Q400.2_2_TEXT: Providing inaccurate drug discovery data or misleading personalized treatment advice directly challenges GSK’s mission to “get ahead of disease together” and “positively impact health.” Misinformation can lead to unsafe treatments and undermine patient trust, conflicting with the goal to improve health outcomes globally.
Q400.2_3_TEXT: While privacy breaches are serious, they do not inherently conflict with the mission if managed properly through strong safeguards. Protecting patient and intellectual property data supports the mission by maintaining trust and enabling secure innovation.
Q400.2_7_TEXT: Failures in AI-driven maintenance or treatment systems threaten patient safety and manufacturing reliability, conflicting with the mission to harness technology and talent to advance health outcomes. Such failures risk delays in delivering safe, effective healthcare solutions.
